Ogun State Commissioner for Health, Dr Tomi Coker yesterday disclosed that three million people in the state are at risk of contacting Neglected Tropical Diseases (NTDs) which included leprosy. She hinted that the state was prone to six NTDs which included onchocerciasis, lymphatic filariasis, schistosomiasis, soil transmitted helminthes, leprosy and buruli ulcer. Coker disclosed this on Wednesday at a press conference in Abeokuta to commemorate this year’s edition of World NTDs day, with the theme ‘Beat NTDs: For Good For All.’ She said out of the 3 million people, 1.4 million were school age children, saying that several people are battling with the complications of the diseases. The commissioner explained that NTDs were group of infectious diseases usually associated with poverty and were found mainly in the tropics. “Though NTDs are associated with low mortality, the burden of the diseases is huge with many of the sufferers developing disabilities with negative socioeconomic consequences,” she said. Zamfara most vulnerable to NTD, says health expert Kwara Govt set up committee to eliminate river blindness Burden of neglected diseases in Sokoto